pergunta: who governs in america’s representative democracy (republic) system

pergunta: which piece of legislation placed the protections in the european convention on human rights
resposta: The European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR) is not a piece of legislation that was placed or enacted in Europe  but rather an international treaty. It was drafted in 1950 and came into force on September 3  1953. The ECHR aims to protect human rights  including the right to life  freedom from slavery  freedom of thought  conscience and religion  and many other civil  political  economic  social  and cultural rights.  The Convention itself is not a piece of legislation that can be placed or enacted in any particular country  but rather an agreement between its member states to uphold the human rights outlined within it. Each signatory state is responsible for implementing the ECHR into their own legal system. In some European countries  this has been done through constitutional amendments or the adoption of national laws.  For example  in the United Kingdom  the Human Rights Act 1998 was enacted to give effect to the ECHR within the UK's legal system. This legislation places a duty on public authorities in the UK to act in accordance with the Convention rights and allows individuals to bring claims against public authorities for breaches of those rights

pergunta: in humans what determines the gender of the offspring
resposta: In humans  the gender of the offspring is determined by the sex chromosomes carried by the sperm and the egg. A sperm can carry either an X or a Y chromosome. An egg can only carry an X chromosome. If a sperm with an X chromosome fertilizes an egg  the resulting offspring will be female (XX). If a sperm with a Y chromosome fertilizes an egg  the resulting offspring will be male (XY). Therefore  the gender of the offspring is not determined by the parents' genders or their physical characteristics  but rather by which sex chromosome is contributed by each parent.

pergunta: where was the eastern front located in ww1
resposta: The Eastern Front during World War I referred to the theater of war between the Russian Empire and the Central Powers (primarily Germany  Austria-Hungary  and Bulgaria) in Eastern Europe. It extended from the Baltic Sea in the north to the Black Sea in the south  and from the Carpathian Mountains in the west to the Caucasus Mountains in the east.  The major battles on the Eastern Front included the Galician Offensive (1914)  the Brusilov Offensive (1916)  and the Battle of Riga (1917). The front line shifted frequently throughout the war  with significant territorial gains and losses for both sides.  It's important to note that the Eastern Front was a much larger theater of war than the Western Front  which is often more well-known due to its impact on world history through the involvement of France  Britain  and the United States. However  the Eastern Front saw some of the bloodiest battles and highest casualty rates of World War I.
